      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Many of AVFoundation’s key features and capabilities relate to playing and processing media assets. The framework models assets with the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avasset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " class, which is an abstract, immutable type representing a single media resource. It provides a composite view of a media asset that models the static aspects of the media as a whole. An instance of "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avasset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " can represent local file-based media, such as a QuickTime movie or an MP3 audio file, and can also represent an asset progressively downloaded from a remote host or streamed using HTTP Live Streaming (HLS)."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avasset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " simplifies working with media in two important ways. First, it provides a level of independence from the media format. It gives you a consistent interface for managing and interacting with your media regardless of its underlying type. The framework manages the details of working with container formats and codec types to the framework, leaving you to focus on how you want to use the media assets in your app."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Second, "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avasset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " provides a level of independence from the media’s location. You create an asset instance by initializing it with the media’s URL. This could be a local URL, such as one contained within your app bundle or elsewhere on the file system, or it could be a resource, such as an HLS stream hosted on a remote server. In either case, the framework performs the work necessary to efficiently retrieve and load the media in a timely manner on your behalf. Removing the burdens of dealing with media formats and locations greatly simplifies working with audiovisual media."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avasset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " is a container object composed of one or more instances of "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avassettrack"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", which models the asset’s uniformly-typed media streams. The most commonly used track types are audio and video tracks, but asset tracks also model other supplementary tracks, such as closed captions, subtitles, and timed metadata."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "image",
              "identifier": "media-2945066",
              "metadata": {
                "anchor": "2945066",
                "title": "Figure 1"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You retrieve an asset’s collection of tracks using its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/avfoundation/avasset/1387953-tracks"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. In many cases, you’ll want to perform operations on a subset of an asset’s tracks rather than on its complete collection. In these cases, "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "AVAsset"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " also provides methods to retrieve subsets of tracks based on criteria such as identifier, media type, or characteristic."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
